    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Crescent-shaped nose ornaments made from gold. Postclassic Nahuas of central Mexico associated this symbol with the Huastec region and with deities of octli (pulque), an alcoholic beverage made from fermented agave sap.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Adornos nasales en forma de media luna y hechos de oro. Los nahuas del México central posclásico asociaron este símbolo con la región huasteca y con las deidades del octli (pulque), una bebida alcohólica hecha a partir de la savia de agave fermentada.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tlamantli yehyectzin ipan yacatzolli quence metztli huan tlachihualli ica teocuitlatl. Nahuatl tlen Mexco central posclasico quinehpanohqueh ica ce tlaixnextilli tlen Huasteca huan ica totiotzitzin tlen pulqueh ce tlaoniliztli tlen teohuihtia huan tlachihualli ica iayoh metl tlen tentzitzicaztic.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Eastern Huasteca Nahuatl</Note_Language>
